WEBVTT

00:09.009 --> 00:11.044
Oh, this one's
from your mom.

00:11.444 --> 00:14.447
Oh... kitten
in a basket of yarn.

00:14.781 --> 00:16.716
"Dear Niles,

00:17.017 --> 00:19.586
I know we haven't always
gotten along."

00:25.592 --> 00:26.926
Isn't that sweet?

00:27.193 --> 00:29.029
FRASIER:
Hey, Niles

00:29.262 --> 00:31.297
look what I found
in the parking lot.

00:31.297 --> 00:33.566
Hi, Niles.
It's good to see you.

00:33.767 --> 00:34.300
How's he doing?

00:34.801 --> 00:36.669
The doctor says
he's just great.

00:36.936 --> 00:38.505
Well, he looks just great.

00:38.505 --> 00:40.440
(whispers):
Why is he so pale?

00:40.774 --> 00:42.675
(whispers):
He's always this pale.

00:42.942 --> 00:44.477
I'll take those.

00:44.944 --> 00:46.012
Well, Niles,
you've got

00:46.012 --> 00:48.448
quite an impressive
array of flowers here.

00:48.448 --> 00:50.917
Uh... Oh, dear Lord.

00:51.251 --> 00:52.652
Who sent mums?

00:52.952 --> 00:55.021
Those are from Jaime,
our squash valet.

00:55.021 --> 00:55.955
Really?

00:56.289 --> 00:57.357
You know, when I had the flu,

00:57.357 --> 00:58.858
Jaime didn't send me
so much as a card.

00:59.292 --> 01:00.360
You didn't have the flu.

01:00.360 --> 01:01.661
You barely had the sniffles.

01:01.661 --> 01:02.929
I almost threw up.

01:02.929 --> 01:04.330
Who knows?

01:04.330 --> 01:06.232
Mums might have been just
the thing to cheer me up.

01:06.232 --> 01:08.468
I guess we'll never know now, will we?

01:08.468 --> 01:11.137
I'm so sorry you have
to go through all this, Niles.

01:11.137 --> 01:14.040
Oh, I'm pretty used to him by now.

01:14.040 --> 01:14.941
Oh, right...

01:14.941 --> 01:17.811
The... um, yes,
well... thank you.

01:17.811 --> 01:20.346
Who knew all those years
of foie gras and brie

01:20.346 --> 01:22.215
would finally catch up with me.

01:22.515 --> 01:23.583
You know, Frasier,

01:23.583 --> 01:25.085
you might want to get yourself
checked out.

01:25.085 --> 01:26.453
You eat a lot
of that stuff, too.

01:26.453 --> 01:28.788
Yes, but I also drink
a lot of red wine.

01:28.788 --> 01:30.590
Now, Niles,
you'll be happy to know

01:30.590 --> 01:32.425
that your prognosis
is excellent.

01:32.926 --> 01:34.394
I have done some research.
Ah.

01:34.394 --> 01:37.363
I have detailed the procedure
and made copies for each of you.

01:37.363 --> 01:38.298
Here we are.

01:38.298 --> 01:40.100
I also took
the liberty

01:40.100 --> 01:42.035
of checking out your surgeon.

01:42.035 --> 01:43.303
A fine choice.

01:43.503 --> 01:47.073
True, he did have a few brushes
with the law as an undergrad

01:47.073 --> 01:48.541
and I think you all know

01:49.075 --> 01:50.844
how I feel about Tulane's medical school.

01:51.578 --> 01:53.012
But...

01:53.012 --> 01:55.448
on the bright side, he has been
extensively published

01:55.448 --> 01:56.916
and his reputation is stellar.

01:56.916 --> 01:59.385
Now, if you'll all please turn
to page 17 in your handouts.

01:59.886 --> 02:00.854
Where is Dad?

02:00.854 --> 02:02.388
He stepped outside for some coffee.

02:02.388 --> 02:05.391
Oh, I specifically used
laymen's terms for his benefit

02:05.892 --> 02:06.726
Well, all right.

02:06.726 --> 02:08.895
How's he handling all this?

02:08.895 --> 02:10.196
He's positively chirpy.

02:10.196 --> 02:12.132
.
In other words, he's terrified

02:12.132 --> 02:14.067
,
FRASIER:
Yes, when we were kids

02:14.067 --> 02:16.536
whenever one of us
was sick or hurt,

02:16.536 --> 02:18.538
Dad would try to keep us
from worrying

02:19.038 --> 02:21.541
by pretending the problem
didn't even exist.

02:21.541 --> 02:23.910
Nonchalance was his coping mechanism.

02:24.210 --> 02:26.179
Things always turned out
all right, though.

02:27.747 --> 02:29.716
It will this time, too.

02:31.251 --> 02:32.785
How are you holding up?

02:32.785 --> 02:34.287
Well, you know...

02:34.721 --> 02:35.788
You know what?

02:35.788 --> 02:38.258
I think you should think of
something really cool to do

02:38.258 --> 02:40.293
when all this is over--
like a big trip.

02:40.293 --> 02:42.262
That way, you can have something
good to focus on.

02:42.662 --> 02:46.533
I can't think about that
right now.

02:48.101 --> 02:50.403
What the hey?
You still in bed?

02:50.403 --> 02:51.938
It's 9:00
in the morning

02:52.438 --> 02:53.940
Up and at 'em, lazy bones.

02:53.940 --> 02:56.242
Hello, I'm your anesthesiologist, Dr. Ling.

02:56.442 --> 02:57.010
Oh, hello.

02:57.510 --> 02:58.411
How are you
feeling today?

02:58.745 --> 02:59.779
Oh, don't let
this faker fool you.

02:59.779 --> 03:01.214
He's just trying
to get out of work.

03:01.581 --> 03:02.649
,
If you're feeling at all anxious

03:02.649 --> 03:03.650
I can give you
a mild sedative.

03:03.650 --> 03:04.918
No, thanks.

03:04.918 --> 03:05.652
Are you sure, Niles?

03:05.652 --> 03:07.020
Dr. Ling went to Duke.

03:07.020 --> 03:11.658
(phone rings)

03:11.658 --> 03:13.126
Hello?

03:13.126 --> 03:15.628
Can I ask who's calling?

03:15.628 --> 03:17.063
Just a minute, please.

03:17.063 --> 03:17.997
It's Maris.

03:18.498 --> 03:19.966
Do you want me to make up
an excuse?

03:19.966 --> 03:22.350
No, that's okay,
I'll talk to her.

03:23.970 --> 03:24.804
Thank you.

03:26.172 --> 03:28.208
Hello?

03:28.208 --> 03:31.211
Well, yes. How did you hear?

03:31.211 --> 03:34.013
Ah... Jaime is a bit
of a gossip.

03:34.013 --> 03:36.216
Luckily,
they discovered the blockage

03:36.216 --> 03:39.118
before I had a major event.

03:39.118 --> 03:41.120
Well, thank you.

03:41.120 --> 03:43.990
That wasn't the nurse,
that was my wife.

03:44.290 --> 03:46.259
Yes. Daphne.

03:46.259 --> 03:48.661
We were married
a couple of months ago.

03:48.661 --> 03:52.165
.
No, well, uh, that's not really my fault
you didn't know

03:52.165 --> 03:55.001
Sounds to me like your argument
is with Jaime.

03:56.970 --> 03:58.037
Well, if it makes you
feel any better,

03:58.538 --> 03:59.038
we didn't invite anyone.

03:59.505 --> 04:00.540
Dr. Ling...

04:03.209 --> 04:05.111
Uh-huh. Uh-huh

04:05.111 --> 04:10.016
Yes, of course we invited him,
he's my brother.

04:10.016 --> 04:11.985
Yes: Williams-Sonoma
and Tiffany's.

04:11.985 --> 04:13.519
Keep it coming.

04:18.358 --> 04:19.358
Now, in just a few moments,

04:19.358 --> 04:21.293
we'll be ready to wheel you down to the O.R.

04:21.594 --> 04:22.662
He'll receive general anesthesia

04:22.662 --> 04:24.163
once he's on
the operating table.

04:24.163 --> 04:26.666
Now, if you'd like to follow
along in your handouts,

04:26.666 --> 04:27.667
I could take you through

04:27.667 --> 04:29.102
the first steps
of the procedure.

04:29.435 --> 04:31.504
The doctor explained everything
to us yesterday.

04:31.938 --> 04:33.506
Yes, but did he have
an mnemonic verse

04:34.007 --> 04:36.376
that goes along to the tune
of "Camptown Races"?

04:36.376 --> 04:37.644
Hello.
Ah...

04:38.077 --> 04:39.145
Dr. Schafer,
I was just explaining

04:39.145 --> 04:40.580
my brother's procedure
to my family.

04:40.947 --> 04:42.482
I'll hand the floor
over to you.

04:42.482 --> 04:43.816
Thank you...?

04:44.083 --> 04:45.585
Frasier...Dr.Crane.

04:45.952 --> 04:46.519
Oh, great.

04:47.020 --> 04:47.520
Once you're under,

04:48.021 --> 04:49.522
we'll begin by
inserting some tubes

04:49.522 --> 04:50.857
to monitor your blood pressure

04:51.124 --> 04:52.692
Then while one team harvests
the saphenous vein

04:53.159 --> 04:54.027
from your right leg,

04:54.027 --> 04:56.195
I'll be opening up your chest.

04:56.195 --> 04:56.996
Excuse me, uh...

04:56.996 --> 04:58.331
If I may, um...

04:58.331 --> 05:00.233
wouldn't a mid-CAB
be less invasive?

05:00.733 --> 05:02.735
I have done some research
into the matter

05:02.735 --> 05:05.672
and I believe that is
the prevailing methodology.

05:05.672 --> 05:07.940
Well, you may have read
about that in Reader's Digest,

05:07.940 --> 05:09.809
but a mid-CAB is
only appropriate

05:09.809 --> 05:11.811
for limited blockages.

05:11.811 --> 05:14.314
My source is not
Reader's Digest.

05:14.314 --> 05:16.182
It is a Harvard colleague.

05:16.182 --> 05:19.552
Harvard being my alma mater.

05:19.552 --> 05:21.054
Harvard!

05:21.554 --> 05:22.555
,
Now, if I'm not mistaken

05:22.555 --> 05:24.957
the blockage is in the left
anterior descending artery.

05:24.957 --> 05:26.392
And the right coronary,

05:26.392 --> 05:27.393
Look, in my expert opinion

05:27.393 --> 05:29.662
I'm doing what's best for this patient.

05:29.662 --> 05:31.397
And my expert opinion
says otherwise.

05:31.397 --> 05:32.398
Well, if you're such an expert,

05:32.899 --> 05:33.900
maybe you should perform
the surgery.

05:33.900 --> 05:36.369
Maybe I should.
Dad.

05:36.369 --> 05:39.172
Frasier, you are not operating
on your brother.

05:39.172 --> 05:40.006
Suit yourself.

05:40.006 --> 05:42.008
LING:
Maybe it would be best

05:42.008 --> 05:43.509
if everyone stepped out

05:43.509 --> 05:45.378
while Dr. Schafer
talks to the patient.

05:45.378 --> 05:46.713
Mrs. Crane,
you're welcome to stay.

05:47.747 --> 05:49.248
Niles, I'll...

05:49.248 --> 05:51.017
I'll see you before
they wheel you in.

05:58.491 --> 05:59.926
Well, I'll tell you one thing

05:59.926 --> 06:01.394
about that Dr. Schafer's
people skills:

06:01.394 --> 06:02.395
I am not a fan.

06:02.395 --> 06:03.930
Oh, will you leave it alone?

06:03.930 --> 06:04.931
You're being a big pain.

06:04.931 --> 06:07.200
Yes, well, I happen
to know a thing or...

06:07.200 --> 06:09.035
a thing or two
about bypass surgery.

06:09.035 --> 06:11.037
He was totally
condescending to me.

06:11.037 --> 06:13.873
He was just trying to
let you know who's in charge.

06:13.873 --> 06:15.708
I'm sure, at the first sign of trouble,

06:15.708 --> 06:17.677
he'll run right out here
to consult with you.

06:21.547 --> 06:22.915
This is so weird.

06:22.915 --> 06:25.418
24 hours ago,
we didn't even know anything

06:25.418 --> 06:26.886
was wrong with Niles.

06:26.886 --> 06:28.855
It just goes to show

06:28.855 --> 06:30.723
you can't take a second
for granted.

06:30.723 --> 06:32.158
Sure can't.

06:32.158 --> 06:34.660
Can't take people for granted, either.

06:34.660 --> 06:35.661
You just never know.

06:36.162 --> 06:37.063
It's true.

06:37.063 --> 06:39.999
That's why you should always
tell the people you love

06:40.500 --> 06:41.968
just how much
they mean to you.

06:41.968 --> 06:44.871
Well, I hope you guys know
how much I care about you.

06:44.871 --> 06:46.272
Oh, geez, sure we do.

06:46.272 --> 06:47.774
And we care about you, too, Roz.

06:47.774 --> 06:49.142
Of course, Roz;
you're like family.

06:49.142 --> 06:50.376
And, Dad...

06:50.376 --> 06:51.744
I hope you know I love you

06:52.245 --> 06:53.646
even at your most difficult.

06:53.646 --> 06:55.114
Well, I love you, too, son,

06:55.615 --> 06:57.617
even when you treat me
like a child.

06:57.617 --> 07:01.320
Frasier bosses everyone around--
it's just his way.

07:01.587 --> 07:02.655
Perhaps if people
behaved more competently,

07:02.655 --> 07:03.589
I wouldn't be so bossy.

07:03.956 --> 07:05.024
Maybe you wouldn't be so bossy

07:05.024 --> 07:06.959
if you didn't always focus on how everybody else behaves.

07:06.959 --> 07:08.928
That'd be the day.
Yes, well, maybe
that's because

07:08.928 --> 07:10.196
human behavior is my profession.

07:10.196 --> 07:12.365
n take a day off
once in a while.

07:12.365 --> 07:13.065
No kidding.

07:13.433 --> 07:14.967
Who asked you, Roz?

07:14.967 --> 07:17.937
Niles is going off
to surgery soon.

07:17.937 --> 07:19.705
Come and wish him well.

07:19.705 --> 07:22.508
You know...
we really should tell her

07:22.508 --> 07:24.911
how much
she means to us, too.

07:24.911 --> 07:27.346
How are you feeling?

07:27.346 --> 07:29.348
I'm a little woozy.

07:29.348 --> 07:31.851
Maybe I should lie down.

07:32.351 --> 07:35.354
Oh, now, Daphne, you know
all the important papers

07:35.354 --> 07:37.256
are in my top
left-hand drawer...

07:37.256 --> 07:39.659
DAPHNE:
Let's not talk
about that right now.

07:39.659 --> 07:40.593
You just relax.

07:40.593 --> 07:44.030
Okay, Daphne.

07:44.030 --> 07:47.533
You know, Daphne, they do these
procedures hundreds of times.

07:47.533 --> 07:48.534
I know

07:49.035 --> 07:51.471
Okay. It's practically
routine, Daphne.

07:51.471 --> 07:54.907
Why do you keep saying my name?

07:54.907 --> 07:57.910
I just want to say it
as many times as I can.

07:57.910 --> 07:59.312
Daphne.

08:01.714 --> 08:03.483
What? Still in bed?

08:03.683 --> 08:04.750
Look at this goldbrick

08:04.750 --> 08:07.253
Well, if you're going to be loafing around all day,

08:07.253 --> 08:09.522
you might as well
have something to read.

08:09.522 --> 08:13.359
I know how you love
your Archies.

08:13.359 --> 08:15.194
Thanks, Dad.

08:15.194 --> 08:18.798
Oh, a Jughead Double Digest.

08:21.601 --> 08:23.603
.
I'll be here waiting for you

08:23.603 --> 08:25.071
I love you, son.

08:25.071 --> 08:27.473
I love you, too.

08:29.876 --> 08:30.810
Frasier.

08:30.810 --> 08:33.246
I have a confession to make.

08:33.246 --> 08:34.746
Hmm?

08:34.746 --> 08:37.250
Remember when we were kids and
I was wearing your opera cape

08:37.750 --> 08:39.085
and you pushed me
down the stairs?

08:39.085 --> 08:41.453
Yes.

08:41.453 --> 08:45.725
You didn't push me.

08:45.725 --> 08:47.527
I jumped.

08:47.527 --> 08:50.863
I was trying to fly
like a Valkyrie.

08:52.732 --> 08:54.166
That's not important right now

08:54.166 --> 08:57.570
The important thing is
that you get well, all right?

08:57.570 --> 08:59.572
Dr. Crane, Mrs. Crane, it's that time.

08:59.572 --> 09:01.007
Ooh.

09:01.374 --> 09:03.442
Okay, we're going to need you
to slide over.

09:03.442 --> 09:07.246
Boy, the hospital's an
interesting place, isn't it?

09:07.246 --> 09:09.515
How so, Niles?
Oh

09:09.882 --> 09:12.852
all roads lead to the hospital.

09:13.219 --> 09:16.789
We're born here,
we get sick here,

09:17.290 --> 09:20.226
and we get well here..

09:20.593 --> 09:22.595
always these big, dramatic moments

09:22.595 --> 09:25.665
and the hospital
just gobbles them up.

09:28.367 --> 09:30.937
You think a hospital
has memories?

09:31.437 --> 09:33.439
I bet it does.

09:33.439 --> 09:36.442
I bet when I walked in,
it thought...

09:36.442 --> 09:38.945
"Oh, you again.

09:38.945 --> 09:42.448
"You're the little boy
who broke his leg in 1966.

09:42.949 --> 09:45.451
Hello, old friend."

09:45.952 --> 09:48.454
Wow, a talking hospital.

09:48.454 --> 09:50.957
That would be cool.

09:50.957 --> 09:53.292
When are these drugs
going to kick in?

09:53.526 --> 09:55.094
I don't know
why I need surgery...

09:55.595 --> 09:57.096
this is the best I've felt in years.

09:57.096 --> 09:58.064
Easy... easy...

09:58.464 --> 10:00.900
Daphne, Daphne, Daphne,

10:03.936 --> 10:05.471
Okay, you ready to take
a little trip

10:05.972 --> 10:06.906
I think he already is.

10:06.906 --> 10:08.708
Can I just have a second?

10:08.708 --> 10:10.643
Of course.

10:14.113 --> 10:15.982
I'll be here
when you wake up.

10:16.282 --> 10:17.350
Promise?

10:17.350 --> 10:18.851
I promise.

